A logical model representing Environmental Control and Life Support Systems (ECLSS) parameters monitored in spacecraft habitat modules.
Measurement of atmospheric gas composition
Oxygen concentration in cabin air, typically around 21%. Crucial for breathing; must stay in safe range to avoid hypoxia or fire risk.

comment.value: Target is approximately 21%. Alert if below 19.5% (hypoxia risk) or above 23% (fire hazard).

definition.value: Carbon dioxide concentration in cabin air, measured in parts per million (ppm).

comment.value: Kept low (thousands of ppm) to prevent crew headaches, dizziness. Alerts if above allowable limit (NASA 3 mmHg ≈ 4000 ppm 1-hr).

definition.value: Nitrogen concentration in cabin air, typically around 78%.

comment.value: Primary buffer gas to maintain pressure. Changes may indicate pressure adjustments.

definition.value: Methane concentration in cabin air, measured in parts per million (ppm).

comment.value: Typically near 0. Monitored as part of atmospheric quality and as a flammability indicator.

definition.value: Hydrogen concentration in cabin air, measured in parts per million (ppm).

comment.value: Should be approximately 0; any reading flags a leak or issue as hydrogen is flammable.

definition.value: Water vapor partial pressure in cabin air, indicating absolute humidity.

comment.value: Managed to prevent condensation; relates to approximately 40-60% relative humidity comfort range.

Total cabin atmospheric pressure, nominally around 101 kPa.

comment.value: Vital for habitability; deviations can cause decompression risks.

definition.value: Cabin air temperature, kept in 18-27°C safe range.

comment.value: Optimal temperature around 22°C for crew health and comfort.

definition.value: Relative humidity in cabin air, as a percentage.

comment.value: Controlled between 30-60% for comfort with limits at 25-75%. Prevents dry air or condensation issues.

definition.value: Dew point temperature of cabin air in degrees Celsius.

comment.value: Useful for monitoring moisture load and condensation risk. Derived from humidity and temperature.
